## Challenges and Considerations

Despite the many benefits, technology integration in nursing also presents challenges:

- **Increased Screen Time and Workload:** Nurses report spending significant portions of their shifts interacting with EHRs, which can detract from direct patient care and increase cognitive load ([Kossman & Scheidenhelm, 2008](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18317257/)).

- **Potential Impairment of Critical Thinking:** Overreliance on technology may hinder nurses' clinical judgment and decision-making skills if not balanced appropriately ([Kossman & Scheidenhelm, 2008](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18317257/)).

- **Digital Divide and Health Equity:** Access to technology and digital literacy vary among populations, potentially exacerbating health disparities. Nurses must be equipped to address these social determinants of health ([Risling, 2017](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28049072/)).

- **Cost and Resource Intensity:** Emerging technologies such as AI and virtual reality can be expensive and resource-intensive, limiting their availability in underserved regions ([HIMSS, 2020](https://www.himss.org/resources/2020-emerging-technology-global-nursing-care)).

## Future Outlook and Conclusion

The nursing profession is at the forefront of healthcare transformation driven by technology. Nurses are not only users but also innovators and champions of emerging technologies that improve patient care and operational efficiency globally ([HIMSS, 2020](https://www.himss.org/resources/2020-emerging-technology-global-nursing-care)).

To maximize the benefits and mitigate challenges, nursing education must continue evolving to integrate informatics competencies and prepare nurses for a technology-infused practice environment. Continuous professional development and research are essential to document best practices and advance the effective use of technology in nursing.

In conclusion, technology has fundamentally changed nursing by enhancing patient safety, expanding access to care, improving efficiency, and enabling data-driven decision-making. While challenges remain, the ongoing integration of technology promises to further empower nurses and improve healthcare outcomes worldwide.

